Baseball Statistics Regression

Lance Dugger

Problem Description

The moneyball data set is a csv file consisting of 17 columns describing different statistics for baseball teams during the regular season. Each row represents a regular season for a certain team. The data set includes a wins column to indicate how many wins each team had during the season. Different regression methods will be used to develop a model to predict total wins during a season based on a baseball team’s statistics.

Data Preparation

#Remove Index column
moneyball <- subset(moneyball, select = -INDEX)

#Add Base Hit Column
moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_1B <- moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_H - moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_HR - moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_3B -
  moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_2B

#Add no hit column
moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_NH <- moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_BB - moneyball$TEAM_BATTING_SO

#Add stolen base percentage column
moneyball$TEAM_BASERUN_SBP <- moneyball$TEAM_BASERUN_SB/(moneyball$TEAM_BASERUN_SB+moneyball$TEAM_BASERUN_CS)

#Set column number variable so it does not increase as flag columns are added
cols <- ncol(moneyball)

#Iterate through dataframe to correct outliers and NA's
for (i in 1:cols){
  #Add flag column for na's and replace value with median
  moneyball$flagna <- ifelse(is.na(moneyball[[i]]), 1, 0)
  moneyball[[i]][is.na(moneyball[[i]])] = median(moneyball[[i]], na.rm = TRUE)
  
  #Add flag column for outliers and change value to 2nd or 98th percentile
  moneyball$flagout <- if_else(moneyball[[i]] > quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.98) | moneyball[[i]] < quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.02), 1, 0)
  moneyball[[i]] <- ifelse(moneyball[[i]] > quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.98), quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.98), moneyball[[i]])
  moneyball[[i]] <- ifelse(moneyball[[i]] < quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.02), quantile(moneyball[[i]], 0.02), moneyball[[i]])
  
  #Rename flag columns
  moneyball <- rename_with(moneyball, .fn = ~paste0("FLAGNA_", colnames(moneyball[i]), sep = ""), .cols = flagna)
  moneyball <- rename_with(moneyball, .fn = ~paste0("FLAGOUT_", colnames(moneyball[i]), sep = ""), .cols = flagout)
}

# Scatterplot Matrix
panel.cor <- function(x, y, digits=2, prefix="", cex.cor, ...)
{
  usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
  r <- abs(cor(x, y))
  txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits=digits)[1]
  txt <- paste(prefix, txt, sep="")
  if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
  text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = cex.cor * r)
}

Model Creation

#Function for Mean Square Error Calculation
mse <- function(sm) 
  mean(sm$residuals^2)

#Set training and test sets
set.seed(1)
train <- sample(1:nrow(moneyball), as.integer(nrow(moneyball) * .7))
test <- (-train)

# All Subsets Regression

#create predict function for regsubsets
predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id,...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id = id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[,xvars]%*%coefi
}

#Generate 10 folds
k <- 10
set.seed(3)
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(moneyball), replace = TRUE)

#Create matrix to store MSE
cv_errors <- matrix(NA, k, 12, dimnames = list(NULL, paste(1:12)))

#Iterate through each fold and calculate MSE
for(j in 1:k){
  
  best_fit = regsubsets(TARGET_WINS ~ TEAM_BATTING_1B + TEAM_BATTING_2B + TEAM_BATTING_3B + TEAM_BATTING_HR +
                          TEAM_BATTING_NH+ TEAM_BASERUN_SB + TEAM_BASERUN_CS +TEAM_BATTING_HBP + TEAM_PITCHING_H + 
                          TEAM_PITCHING_SO + TEAM_FIELDING_E + TEAM_FIELDING_DP, data = moneyball[folds!=j,], nvmax=12)
  
  for(i in 1:12){
    pred = predict(best_fit, moneyball[folds==j,], id=i)
    cv_errors[j,i] = mean((moneyball$TARGET_WINS[folds==j]-pred)^2)
  }
}

#Plot minimum MSE
mean_cv_errors = apply(cv_errors, 2, mean)
min = which.min(mean_cv_errors)
plot(mean_cv_errors, type='b')
points(min, mean_cv_errors[min][1], col = "red", cex = 2, pch = 20)

#R Squared Funtionc
eval_results <- function(true, predicted, df) {
  SSE <- sum((predicted -true)^2)
  SST <- sum((true - mean(true))^2)
  R_square <- 1 - SSE/SST
  MSE <- SSE/nrow(df)
  out <- paste("R^2:", R_square, "MSE:", MSE,"\n",  sep = "\n")
  cat(out[1])
}

#Print R^2 and MSE for Ridge Regression

Mode Selection

The data was analyzed using three different methods. The first method used was the Best Subset method. This method compares all possible subsets of data and outputs the mean squared error among other statistics. K Folds Cross Validation with ten folds was used to help reduce the variance in the mean squared error reported. After cross validating, the eleven variable model was chosen for the Best Subsets method. Based on the mean squared error being the highest of the three models, this model was not chosen as the final model.

The second method used was Ridge Regression. This method is very similar to the Least Squares approach for linear regression, however there is a shrinkage penalty term that minimizes some of the coefficients for variables. There is a tuning parameter \(\lambda\) that controls the impact of this shrinkage term. The data was split into a training and test set. Ridge Regression was applied to the training set and the \(\lambda\) value that lead to the lowest mean squared error was used. K Folds Cross Validation with ten folds was used to minimize the variance in the mean squared error. Ridge Regression was then applied to the test set using the previously determined \(\lambda\) value.

The third method used was the Lasso. This method is similar to Ridge Regression, however there is an extra term in the equation that allows variable coefficients to equal zero. The data was split into a training and test set. The Lasso was used on the training set and the \(\lambda\) value that lead to the lowest mean squared error was used. K Folds Cross Validation with ten folds was used to minimize the variance in the mean squared error. The Lasso was then applied to the test set using the previously determined \(\lambda\) value. Based on having a lower mean squared error than the Ridge Regression model, the Lasso model was chosen as the final model.
